# URL-Driven State

All meaningful application state MUST be reflected in the URL so that pages survive refresh, can be bookmarked, and can be shared.

## Rules

- Use URL path parameters (e.g., `/analysis/:gameId`, `/game/:roomId`) or query parameters to represent state.
- NEVER rely solely on React Router's `location.state` or in-memory state to drive a page. If the user refreshes the browser, the page must still work.
- When state is too large for the URL (e.g., a full move list), persist it to `localStorage` keyed by the URL identifier, then read it back on load.
- Every routable view must be accessible by its URL alone — no prior navigation required.

## Pattern

```typescript
// Save data before navigating
saveData(id, payload);
navigate(`/feature/${id}`);

// In the target component, load from URL param
const { id } = useParams();
const data = loadData(id);
```
